erations of Mennonites for whom the farm family was the primary social unit. The sectarian, lay-oriented church congregation interpreted life's meaning and enforced strict social boundaries on the community level. These traditionalist were coupled with a sensitive adaptation to the market economy of the outside world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMennoniteszManitobazSteinbach RegionxSocial life and customs. 0aMennoniteszNebraskazJansen RegionxSocial life and customs. 0aMennoniteszRussiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aRussian GermanszManitobazSteinbach RegionxSocial life and customs. 0aRussian GermanszNebraskazJansen RegionxSocial life and customs. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Mennonite.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148757636340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487576363423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487576363.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK